full_text: @violetweather Basically, once you get past the infamous Minotaur and Medusa in SMT4 you're pretty much good. The only tip I'll give you is to try to get Bufu and Zan skills.
full_text(utf-8): b"@violetweather Basically, once you get past the infamous Minotaur and Medusa in SMT4 you're pretty much good. The only tip I'll give you is to try to get Bufu and Zan skills."

full_text: @violetweather Devil Summoner Soul Hackers and Strange Journey Redux are also great on 3DS, but I wouldn't recommend them first. Also, be warned that Devil Survivor and SJR are pretty hard. And SMT4 starts out extremely hard for the first few hours but gets easier once you reach a certain area.
full_text(utf-8): b"@violetweather Devil Summoner Soul Hackers and Strange Journey Redux are also great on 3DS, but I wouldn't recommend them first. Also, be warned that Devil Survivor and SJR are pretty hard. And SMT4 starts out extremely hard for the first few hours but gets easier once you reach a certain area."

full_text: @violetweather Go with Devil Survivor for a "bridge" between Persona and SMT, or go with SMT4 to see all the staples and elements of the series. I'd recommend SMT4 first overall, but DS is definitely worth checking out afterward.
full_text(utf-8): b'@violetweather Go with Devil Survivor for a "bridge" between Persona and SMT, or go with SMT4 to see all the staples and elements of the series. I\'d recommend SMT4 first overall, but DS is definitely worth checking out afterward.'

full_text: @violetweather It's basically a sequel to the neutral ending in SMT4. Devil Survivor Overclocked is also a good place to start on 3DS. It's an SRPG but it has a few elements borrowed from Persona, like a more character-focused plot and a time system.
full_text(utf-8): b"@violetweather It's basically a sequel to the neutral ending in SMT4. Devil Survivor Overclocked is also a good place to start on 3DS. It's an SRPG but it has a few elements borrowed from Persona, like a more character-focused plot and a time system."

full_text: @violetweather I'd recommend going with SMT IV if you have a 3DS. Nocturne is a pretty good place to start though, just make sure to go on NORMAL mode. Apparently the new "easy mode" is basically a baby mode, it won't prepare you for the other games at all.
full_text(utf-8): b'@violetweather I\'d recommend going with SMT IV if you have a 3DS. Nocturne is a pretty good place to start though, just make sure to go on NORMAL mode. Apparently the new "easy mode" is basically a baby mode, it won\'t prepare you for the other games at all.'

full_text: @Kloud_Leonhart SMT4 is the best for introducing the main aspects of the series, such as negotiations and the alignments. @R3nster Sorry for the late response
1. Download emulator, game ROM, and Texture Pack
2. Load the ROM once and close it
3. Find the PSP folder on your computer
4. Place the texture pack folder (ULUS10432) inside of the "TEXTURES" folder, and overwrite everything
5. Done
full_text(utf-8):
b'@R3nster Sorry for the late response
1. Download emulator, game ROM, and Texture Pack
2. Load the ROM once and close it
3. Find the PSP folder on your computer
4. Place the texture pack folder (ULUS10432) inside of the "TEXTURES" folder, and overwrite everything
5. Done'

full_text: @dragovian_dude @Jalaxy_Pro @kccrawlingchaos The turn counter is for your entire party. If you get an extra turn from your 2nd party member, then it would still go on to the 3rd until the first round is up. Then it'll loop back again to use the extra turns you got, in this case it'd be your 1st party member.
full_text(utf-8): b"@dragovian_dude @Jalaxy_Pro @kccrawlingchaos The turn counter is for your entire party. If you get an extra turn from your 2nd party member, then it would still go on to the 3rd until the first round is up. Then it'll loop back again to use the extra turns you got, in this case it'd be your 1st party member."

full_text: @dragovian_dude @Jalaxy_Pro @kccrawlingchaos Basically, instead of "one mores", you get a "turn counter" that's starts with how many party members you have. If you hit an enemies weakness, then you get an extra turn to do stuff. If the enemy nullifies your attack, then you lose a turn. The same applies for enemies.

full_text: @mattikarpart BL is a pretty typical main story for the game, GD offers some backstory and lore for the world, CF is a different perspective on the conflict, and Church gives some backstory on the religion and history of the Church
full_text(utf-8): b'@mattikarpart BL is a pretty typical main story for the game, GD offers some backstory and lore for the world, CF is a different perspective on the conflict, and Church gives some backstory on the religion and history of the Church'

full_text: @mattikarpart Blue Lions -> Golden Deer -> Crimson Flower -> Church (splits off of CF) is the recommend order by most by the way, but as I said you can do whatever you want. The most unique route is CF, I won't say why since it's a spoiler but I recommend you do BL or GD before it.
full_text(utf-8): b"@mattikarpart Blue Lions -> Golden Deer -> Crimson Flower -> Church (splits off of CF) is the recommend order by most by the way, but as I said you can do whatever you want. The most unique route is CF, I won't say why since it's a spoiler but I recommend you do BL or GD before it."

full_text: @mattikarpart The Church route is kind of interesting, but the Golden Deer route is extremely similar and practically the same gameplay-wise, and the Golden Deer route is a much better experience.
full_text(utf-8): b'@mattikarpart The Church route is kind of interesting, but the Golden Deer route is extremely similar and practically the same gameplay-wise, and the Golden Deer route is a much better experience.'

full_text: @mattikarpart The exception is in the Red-colored house. In that house, you have to make a decision that splits the route in two. Choosing to defend the Church in this decision will result in what's a worse version of the Yellow-colored route, so I recommend you go with the other option first.
full_text(utf-8): b"@mattikarpart The exception is in the Red-colored house. In that house, you have to make a decision that splits the route in two. Choosing to defend the Church in this decision will result in what's a worse version of the Yellow-colored route, so I recommend you go with the other option first."

full_text: @mattikarpart When you start playing don't worry about which house to choose, just go with whatever you're most interested in. I recommend you play the other routes afterward to get a better perspective, each one is completely different (with one exception)
full_text(utf-8): b"@mattikarpart When you start playing don't worry about which house to choose, just go with whatever you're most interested in. I recommend you play the other routes afterward to get a better perspective, each one is completely different (with one exception)"
